air. If it has exactly one same-topic pair, it's counted once. If it has two same-topic pairs, all three share the same topic (since if p1,p2 share topic and p1,p3 share topic, all three share). But as shown, all-same-topic triples have all distinct difficulties, so they're not bad. So each bad triple is counted exactly once. \u2713\n\nBut wait \u2014 the bad triple also needs a same-difficulty pair. The code counts triples where there's a same-topic pair AND the third element shares a difficulty with one of the pair. But the third element sharing a difficulty with one of the pair means there IS a same-difficulty pair. However, what about bad triples where the same-difficulty pair is NOT involving the same-topic pair's members?\n\nActually no \u2014 if the triple has a same-topic pair {pi, pj} and a same-difficulty pair, the same-difficulty pair could be {pi, pk} or {pj, pk} or {pi, pj}. Since pi, pj have distinct difficulties (same topic), the same-difficulty pair must involve pk. So bk == bi or bk == bj. The code handles this correctly. \u2713\n\nWhat about bad triples where no pair shares a topic but some pair shares a difficulty? Those aren't bad \u2014 all topics different means the condition is satisfied, so the triple is valid regardless of difficulties. The \"bad\" definition requires topics NOT all different (i.e., some pair shares topic) AND difficulties NOT all different. \u2713\n\nLet me verify with the examples:\n- Example 1: n=4, total=4, expected=3, so bad=1.\n- Example 2: n=5, total=10, expected=10, so bad=0.\n\nThe logic seems correct. Let me check for potential issues with the O(n\u00b2) loop within `by_topic`. If one topic has m problems, the inner loop is O(m\u00b2). Sum of m\u00b2 could be O(n\u00b2) in worst case (all same topic), which with n=2\u00b710\u2075 would be 4\u00b710\u00b9\u2070 \u2014 **TLE**.\n\n{\"verdict\": \"FAIL\", \"bugs\": [{\"description\": \"TLE: The nested loop over pairs within each topic group is O(m^2) per group. If man